 forces a string viewpoint.
 Thus, just to keep things simple, this section focuses on paths of point
 particles.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This poses a challenge: how to write down a collection of paths, in such
 a way that they cover some manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 in some space-filling or maybe some ergodic way.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ergodic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has a specific, narrow definition, so we must be carefull with it's use.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

space-filling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 implies that the collection of paths will come arbitrarily close to every
 point in the manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 might be Minkowski space, or it might be some manifold in general, or some
 subset of a (psuedo-)Riemannian manifold.
 Thus, in formulas, we are looking for a function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:\left[0,1\right]\times S\to M
\]

\end_inset

for some set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 has to be dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

, the tangent manifold.
 That is, not only must 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 come close to every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, but the derivative
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\varphi}\left(t,s\right)=\left.\frac{d\varphi\left(t,s\right)}{dt}\right|_{s=\mbox{const}}
\]

\end_inset

has to come close to every tangent vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 for every point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 There is also a third condition: the 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\varphi}$
\end_inset

 will be appearing as the kinetic terms in some Lagrangian, and, in general,
 the action will need to be finite.
 Thus, one needs that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int dt\left\Vert \dot{\varphi}\left(t,s\right)\right\Vert ^{2}<\infty
\]

\end_inset

for some suitable metric 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

? Well, for starters, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 cannot be a finite set.
 A single space-filling curve could cover all of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and, with some work, could also cover all of 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 but, in that case, it would fail to have a finite kinetic term.
 (This is presumably obvious.) Thus, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has to be at least countable.
 Can it be uncountable? Well, not really, because we have a fourth condition
 to satisfy: we are trying to write down a measure of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\left[d\varphi\right]\exp-\beta A
\]

\end_inset

for some action 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The integral part 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\left[d\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 is understood to be a sum over all paths parameterized by the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is uncountable, then we have formal difficulties with defining the integral.
 Our imagination allows us to imagine 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\left[d\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 as a countable sum over infinitessimals; it does not stretch so far as
 to be an uncountable sum over infinitessimals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But this is all very abstract; perhaps too abstract.
 There four distinct tasks in front of us.
 One is to write down a plausible version of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 that is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

.
 Another is to write down 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 so that it is a convenient parameter.
 We've already concluded that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has to be countable, so we could just use the natural numbers, but this
 might not be entirely 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

convenient
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 More in just a moment.
 Third, we have to write down some explicit expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\left[d\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 that is tractable, and, fourth, to write down the measure
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu=\left[d\varphi\right]\exp-\beta A
\]

\end_inset

so that it is also tractable.
 Note the above does not have the integral symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\int$
\end_inset

 in it, and we wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu$
\end_inset

 for the measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Parameterizing paths
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets now try to construct some plausible 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 We'll do this in several steps.
 First, fix some smooth curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma:\left[0,1\right]\to M
\]

\end_inset

This can be any curve, but the intent is that it will probably be a geodesic,
 at the end.
 Next, select a path 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}^{n}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the dimension of the tangent bundle.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M\approx\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, and we are using the atlas to reinterpret, by abuse of notation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi:\left[0,1\right]\to TM
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi\left(t\right)\in T_{\gamma\left(t\right)}M
\]

\end_inset

Having picked such a 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, we then use the exp map to create the final curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\left(t\right)=\gamma\left(t\right)\exp\psi\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

This is to be read as saying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

starting at point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\gamma\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, use polar coordinates to travel in a direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, for a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\left(t\right)\right|$
\end_inset

, to arrive at a new point 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\prime}=\varphi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Holding 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 fixed, it should be apparent that all we really need is a family of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 that is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in order to arrive at a family of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 that is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 What is not yet obvious is that this construction is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

.
 To get dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

, we need to consider all diffeomorphisms in the paramter 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Well, one thing at a time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How should we parameterize a collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

? Well, the traditional, conventional choice in QM textbooks is to use some
 family of orthonormal functions on the unit interval.
 In order to get a reasonable parameterization, this family must exhibit
 uniform convergence on the unit interval.
 In Appendix D, we consider a wavelet basis, as opposed to some more convetional
 orthoganl polynomials or even a discrete fourier basis.
 Why wavelets? Because they are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

local
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: they allow one to consider a variation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 that is localized to some small region of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

; this localized variation corresponds to a specific, local subset of the
 wavelets.
 By contrast, a discrte sine & cosine basis requires tweaking all of the
 expansion coefficients, not just some of them, when considering a small
 variation in the path.
 This makes writing delta-epsilon changes harder, and showing uniform convergenc
e harder.
 I think.
 It seems like the localized properties of wavelets should be appealing
