\begin_layout Standard
This appendix develops the idea of a wavelet basis for paths through a manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Haar wavelets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section describes Haar basis wavelets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is given by a function 
\begin_inset Formula $w:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mother wavelet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, that has some desirable properties: Typically, that it is differntiable,
 that it is zero on the boundaries, ideally with derivative zero at the
 boundaries, and non-zero in the middle.
 Then, given a finite-length bit-string 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{k};k=1,\cdots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 define the wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\left\{ b\right\} }:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(t\right)=w\left(t;\left\{ b_{k}\right\} \right)=\begin{cases}
w\left(2^{n}t-c_{\left\{ b\right\} }\right) & \frac{c_{\left\{ b\right\} }}{2^{n}}\le t\le\frac{c_{\left\{ b\right\} }+1}{2^{n}}\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{\left\{ b\right\} }=\sum_{k=1}^{n}b_{k}2^{k}
\]

\end_inset

Each set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 corresponds one-to-one to a dyadic rational 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\left\{ b\right\} }/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 and thus the wavelets form a countable basis for the unit interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arbitrary functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 can be approximated in the wavelet basis with a sequence of constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(x\right)\approx\sum_{\left\{ b\right\} }a_{\left\{ b\right\} }w_{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

The above is not quite correct, because we've arranged the 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 to vanish at the dyadic rationals.
 I need to crack open a book on wavelets to get a more precise definition,
 and also a proof that the above forms a complete basis, and that it converges
 uniformly.
 I beleive such a basis is possible, in general.
\end_layout

